New Records: Ireland secured their third win over England in the T20 World Cup, with two previous victories in the ODI format.
Key Match Events: The match was decided via the Duckworth-Lewis method due to rain, with Ireland achieving a target of 110 after being 105-5 in 14.3 overs.
Ireland's Andy Balbirnie scored 62 off 47 balls, his eighth T20I fifty, and contributed to a 82-run second wicket partnership with Lorcan Tucker.
England's Liam Livingstone and Mark Wood took three wickets each, turning the match around after Ireland's strong start.
Ireland's Josh Little dismissed England's Jos Buttler and Alex Hales in quick succession, while Fionn Hand removed Ben Stokes.
The match saw Ireland's collapse after a 92-1 start, with key contributions from Paul Stirling and Dawid Malan.
The victory opened group 1 for Australia as five teams now have two points each.
Post-Match Reflections: Ireland's win was their maiden victory in the Super 12 stage of the T20 World Cup.
Miscellaneous Highlights: The match was rain-affected, with play halted due to showers, and Ireland's win marked their second T20I victory over England.
